cards.title: 10 Clever Hacks to Remove Permanent Marker from Any Surface
cards.abstract: Using permanent marker can be risky—one small slip up and something gets ruined. Wrong! Here, you'll find 10 effective ways to remove permanent marker when it ends up on unintended surfaces in your home. The post 10 Clever Hacks to Remove Permanent Marker from Any Surface appeared first on Family Handyman.

slides.title: Laminate Countertop
slides.body: To carefully remove permanent marker from laminate surfaces without harming the finish or leaving a cloudy residue, just reach into your pantry! Regular vegetable oil works perfectly. There are a couple of steps to this process; click here to see how it's done.

image.title: Remove Permanent Marker on Laminate
image.caption: Dab some cooking oil onto a paper towel and then lay the paper towel over the stain that refuses to budge. Wait a few minutes while the oil works to dissolve the stubborn stain. Finally, remove the towel and rub away the stain in circular motions (with some force) with another paper towel dipped in oil. When the stain is gone, wipe the area clean with soap and water.

slides.title: Clothing
slides.body: Before tossing your permanent marker-stained clothes into the trash, try dabbing the spot with hairspray that contains alcohol. It will help to break down the stain more aggressively than your normal laundry detergent. Let the hairspray sit on the stain for several minutes before washing in the washing machine.

slides.title: Couch and Chair Cushions
slides.body: Accidentally getting permanent marker on your upholstery may seem like a disaster, but sprinkling some baking soda on the mark and scrubbing it with a toothbrush will do the trick. We've all been there, trust me. Book (and TV show) hangovers are real! I hate the feeling of falling so deeply in love with a concept in books or movies, that you don't know what could ever compare. And while Bridgerton is in a league of their own with all the exceptional writing and plot lines, we do have some reads that will give you all the same regency era feels that you're looking to replicate. They're fun, romantic, and witty — just like your fave series! So, keep reading for all the books like Bridgerton to cure that Polin hangover! Bridgerton books

slides.title: Books Like "Bridgerton" To Read Right Now
slides.body:
Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen

We can't forget this regency classic! Probably one of the most famous works of its time, Pride and Prejudice shows how you can find love and happiness when you finally look past your initial judgements (or prejudice) against people. In this case, it was social class, but it can be true of so many societal circumstances. At the end of the day, it's a simple and timeless love story between two people who put their bias and egos aside to see the authenticity in one another.

cards.title: The 25 Best Historical Fiction Books of All Time
cards.abstract: A great novel can take you on a journey through the past and present.

slides.body:
If you love historical fiction, great news: There’s more of it on the shelves than ever, about more time periods, by writers around the globe. While these kinds of books date back to The Epic of Gilgamesh (the classic story of an ancient Mesopotamian king) and Hamlet (the classic story of a medieval Danish king), today’s historical novels deal with all kinds of relevant issues, as well as the love stories and epic family sagas that make us all human.

Two kinds of books up again and again: the beloved bodice rippers, designed to deliver hot, sexy entertainment set in a different era, and historical novels based on actual history, filled with intriguing, accurate detail (see: All the Light We Cannot See), a riveting story (see: The Night Watchman) and topped by beautifully written language (see: Warlight). The latter is tricky to pull off—so much so that we had to make a list of the best of the best historical fiction books, ranging in time periods from ancient Greece to 1960s Saigon.

slides.title: 1) Pachinko, by Min Jin Lee
slides.body:
$11.28

Shop Now

Lee’s mega-bestselling novel about Korean immigrants in Japan. Beginning in rural Korea during the late 19th century, the story starts with the family of a young man named Hoonie, as he gains a wife. Eventually their daughter Sunja will move to Osaka, Japan, where Koreans are considered second-class citizens, and her family members take to work at the city’s hugely popular pachinko parlors, which also symbolize life’s changing luck. Currently adapted for TV on Apple TV, this one has a big-screen future written all over it, given its locations and cast of characters.

slides.title: 2) Alias Grace, by Margaret Atwood
slides.body:

Based on the 1843 real-life murders of a Canadian homeowner and his housekeeper, Alias Graces is told through the perspective of a psychiatrist, Dr. Simon Jordan, who is retained by the court to meet with accused maid Grace Marks, on temporary probation and living in the prison governor’s house. Nothing is quite as it seems in this look at inequality wrapped in a murder mystery that will keep readers guessing to the very end and probably after the end, as well.
